Communicate Data Findings : Loan Data from Prosper by Ilknur Cakir¶

Data Overview¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), loan original amount, borrower income, and many others. For this project, I take a subset of features which is 17 variables out of original 81 variables. So the data has 113,937 samples with 17 variables.

In [1]:
# importing necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from IPython.display import display

%matplotlib inline

I select 17 variables that are given below. I first drop all rows with missing value. One of the variables, namely ProsperScore is credit risk score and ranges from 1 to 10 with 1 representing the worst and 10 representing the best. But there are instances where ProsperScore equals to 11. Assuming it is due to unclean data, I drop all of these instances. Other than that the data is pretty clean and tidy.

Stated Monthly Income¶

The distribution of monthly income is given below. It is not distributed normally and symmetrically and it is highly right-skewed. Monthly income of borrowers is lumped between 0 and 10k. Mean is around 5k. Very small percentage of borrowers make more than 20k. Max is at around 483k.

Log transformation is necessary to make it look more like normally distributed and symmetric. The transformation is done below and new variable is named 'income_trans'. The distributions of stated monthly income and transformed income are given in the upcoming two cells below.

The histograms of borrower rate, borrower APR and lender yield are very similar to each other which makes totally sense. APR includes interest rate that borrowers pay and other service fees. And lender yield is roughly equals to the rate the lender gets from borrower which is interest rate minus some transaction and service fees. Basically all 3 graphs follows borrower's interest rate.

Prosper Score gives the risk score of the borrower. It ranges from 1 to 10 with 1 boing the lowest and 10 being the best score. The distribution has three peaks at the values 4, 6 and 8.

Debt to income ratio is roughly between 0 and 10. There is a small number of samples with debt to income ratio greater than 1. But it goes to as high as 10. The distribution is very right-skewed.

Most samples have no delinquency in the last 7 years. For a small subset of samples, this number can be as high as 80 or 100. The lump is between 0 and 30 in the distribution.

There are spikes at points 5k, 10k, 15k, 20k and 25k in the distribution of loan original amount. It peaks at one spike and decreases until the next one and there it peaks again. It is also slightly right-skewed.

I also add the violinplots of these variables. It gives a different perspective.

So I would expect to see a negative correlation between two. Regression plot and point plot say the same. The average risk score deteriorates as the number of inquiries increases.

To sum up; the credit risk score increases (improves, the higher the better) as

  • stated monthly income increases,
  • the number of delinquencies in the last 7 years decreses,
  • the number of times the borrower checks his score in the last 6 mmonths decreases,
  • the debt to income ratio decreases,

There is no clear relationship between credit risk score and the number of current credit lines.

Next I will try to explore Term variable. Term is the duration over which the borrowers is supposed to pay back the loan. Most loans are 36 month loans. There is a very small number of 12 month loans. It is plausible to expect the borrower rate to increase as term increases holding other things equal. Below are given the graph of borrower rate, apr and lender yield changing with term.

it is interesting to see that the average rate of 36 month loans is greater than the average rate of 60 month loans. It might be the case that generally 60 month loans are solely given to people with high credit scores so it makes the average borrower rate smaller. We will see the reason when we look at multivariate graphs.

Borrower APR decreases with term which seems counterintuitive first, but there might be other things affecting apr. So it needs a closer look. Lender yield and borrower rate graphs are very similar to each other. All 3 variables are given in the same graph below. It is seen that lender yield closely follows borrower rate but borrower apr is a bit different.

What affects the borrower’s APR or interest rate?¶

Borrower Rate and Income¶

I expect to see a positive correlation between borrower rate and income. I use regression plot to see the relationship. I use log transformed new variable income_trans instead of original StatedMonthlyIncome. The confidence interval of regression lige gets larger at small and very large incoem values as there is few data points here. Confidence interval is small when there are many samples at the points. It is seen that there is a negative relationship between income and borrower rate. Intrest rate borrower pays decreases with increasing monthly income. It must be so because as income increaases credit score improves and lender charge a lower interest rate to the borrower but we cannot draw this conclusion from the graph. It does not say anything about causation, it says only about correlation.

Borrower Rate and Credit Risk Score¶

We have seen in the previous section that there is a correlation between term and rate. As term increases, borrower rate generally increases. So the relationship between borrower rate and credit risk score is plotted for different term values, 12 month, 36 month and 60 month. The negative relationship between rate and score is apparent especially for 60 month loans in the plot. But it is not very obvious for 12 and 36 month loans. So I want to look at the distribution of interest rate for different risk score values. For that, I use violin plot, it is given below.

As score increases average rate values decrease. The last regression plots show that this relationship does not change for different term values.

In [36]:
# Scatter plot of interest rate and risk score for different term values.
# First I define plot_data to include only 12, 36 or 60 month loans. Then I plot 
# them with different colors.Legend shows which color is for which term.

plt.figure(figsize = (11,8))
colors = sns.color_palette('colorblind', 3)
for i, color in zip([12, 36, 60], colors):
    plot_data = dff[dff.Term == i]
    sns.scatterplot(data = plot_data, y = 'BorrowerRate', x = 'ProsperScore', color = color,
                   alpha = 0.1)
    
# legend object
legend_obj = []
for color in colors:
    legend_obj.append(plt.scatter([], [], color = color))
    
plt.legend(legend_obj, ['12', '36', '60'], title = 'Term');
plt.title('Borrower Rate vs. Credit Score', fontsize = 13);
plt.xlabel('Score', fontsize = 11)
plt.ylabel('Interest Rate', fontsize = 11 );

It is seen in the violin plot that as score increases, the mean interest rate decreases. Also, for small and large score values the distributions are more compact whereas for middle score values they are more spread. The relationship is even more clear in the pointplot given below. Except at one point, the average interest rate always decreases as score increases. So people with a good credit score get a loan cheaper. In these violin and point plots, we did not take the term into account. It is important to make a dsitinction between different term values since term is another factor affecting interest rates.

The last plot in this subsection gives the regression plot of risk score and interest rate for different values. In all of them, the regression line has a negative slope. So we are sure to say that there is a negative correlation between score and borrower rate.

Borrower Rate and Term¶

Intuitively, we can expect to see a positive correlation between term and interest rate since there is a time value of money. The same amount of money next year worths smaller than the same amount of money this year. If we wait longer to get the money paid back, we want to charge more. In the point plot below, 60-month loans do have a smaller average intrest rate than the 36-month loans. It seems counterintuitive. We might expect to see finer details if we hold credit risk score constant as we know from the previous sebsection that there is a negative correlation between borrower rate and risk score. So I next look at the distributions of borrower rates for different terms are given for 2 different score levels, 4 and 8.

When the score is 4, average rate increases first and decreases from 36-month loans to 60-month loans. For score of 8, average term increases as term increases. So we can say that roughly as term increases borrower rate increases too.

The last plot, heatmap shows how borrower rate changes as risk credit score and term change. When we move vertically over the table, average value of rates decreases as score increases. Moving from left to right in the same row, if score is greater than 6, rates increase, for scores smaller than or equal to 6, average rate increases from 12-month to 36-month but decreases from 36-month to 60-month. All in all, we can say that the relationship between interest rate and term is up to the borrower's risk score.

Correlation with Borrower Rate¶

The price the borrower pays for the loan (borrower's rate) decreases as

  • credit risk score of the borrower increases (for different term values)

  • stated monthly income increases,

  • the debt to income ratio falls,

  • the number of current credit lines increases up to 10, after this value there is no clear correlation

  • the loan original amount increases

  • the term of the loan decreases when the credit score is greater than 6. For scores smaller than 6, borrower's rate decreases as term increases from 36 months to 60 months

  • the number of inquiries in the last 6 months decreases.

At this point, it would be nice to look at credit score distribution of people who get small and large loans and compare these. I define large loans as loans that are at least 15k and small loans as loans at most 10k. The distributions are given below. Large loans (loans greater than 15k) are given to people whose credit score is high. The credit score distribution is left-skewed. It basically means that large loans are not given to (or not borrowed by) people with low credit scores. That is probably the reason why we see a negative correlation between loan amount and interest rate. On the other hand, we see that the credit score distribution of people who borrow small loans is symmetric and kind of uniform. Person with any credit score borrows small loans.

From regression plot above, we see that there is a positive correlation between loan amount and debt ratio for 12-month loans. For 3 and 5-year loans, the slope of the regression plot is small and negative. From joint plot below, for very large loan amounts debt ratio is around 20%. For small amounts, debt ratio is between 0 and 60%. So the plots are indecisive about the relationship between loan amount and debt ratio.

Correlation with Loan Amount¶

The correlation coeeficients between loan amount and other variables are given below. Larger loans generally have higher terms, lower borrower interest rate, borrowers with higher credit scores, higher incomes and higher number of credit lines, lower number of inquiries in the last 6 months. We can summarize the findings in this section as follows:

  • Loans with a large original loan amount have a longer term; while small loans have 12 months term, large loans have 36 or 60 months terms.

  • While small loans can be of any value, large loans are mostly multiples of 5k, ie. 10k, 15k, 20k, 25k...

  • For each term value, the price of the loan gets smaller as the loan amount increases. So large loans generally have smaller interest rates compared to smaller loans.

  • The stated monthly income of borrowers who can take out large loans are larger compared to those of borrowers who take smaller loans

  • Larger loans require good credit scores. For instance, borrower needs to have a credit score of at least 5 to get a loan of 30k or 35k. That s probably the reason why we see a negative correlation between loan amount and interest rate.

  • The debt to income ratios of borrowers who get larger loans are generally lower compared to those who get smaller loans.
